  "title": "Styling guide proposal",
  "body": "# Styling\n\nDefault widgets in `react-instantsearch` comes with some styling already applied and loaded.\n\nWhen styling components, you can decide to either extend or completely replace our default styles, using CSS classes or inline style.\n\nAll widget accepts a theme prop and the theme keys are defined in the widget docs.\n# CSS classes styling\n## Reusing our class names\n\nShow how to style by adding a style.css and redefining our BEM classes\n## Providing your own classes\n\ntheme={yourClasses}\n## Extending the default theme\n\ntheme=extendTheme(defaultTheme, yourClasses)\n# Inline styling\n## Providing inline style\n\ntheme={inlineStyles}\n## Extending our default theme\n\ntheme=extendTheme(defaultTheme, inlineStyles)\n# react-themeable\n\nThe theme={} props accepts any parameter that react-themeable support...\n# Tooling\n\nOnly here we can start talking about some tools we recommend as for CSS modules\n## CSS modules with webpack\n\nYou can use webpack css modules on your side and still extend our themes.\n\nSmall js example, no need to explain how to configure webpack.\n## Localized CSS with babel\n\nDefault themes of react-instantsearch are built with babel.. You can use it with your own code, and load css with insert-css.\n\nSmall js example, no need to explain how to configure babel.\n## insertCss, insertStylesheet\n\nTalk about insert-css and insert-stylesheet modules\n",
